[4] Pennsylvania (Delaware County)
Date: Sun 24 Nov 2019
Source: Daily Times [abridged, edited]
https://www.delcotimes.com/news/wallingford-swarthmore-battles-outbreak-of-whooping-cough/article_d7a3bc0a-0ee1-11ea-a498-b797ac65639e.html


Wallingford-Swarthmore School District officials are urging parents and caregivers to be on the lookout for any signs of whooping cough, a highly contagious respiratory disease. The precautionary notices were issued based on 7 confirmed cases of the disease involving district students since the start of 2019.

On [15 Nov 2019], the principals of several schools, including Strath Haven high school and middle school and Swarthmore-Rutledge Elementary School, advised families their children could have been exposed to whooping cough, also known as pertussis. That was followed by a broader notice from Superintendent Lisa Palmer on [22 Nov 2019] providing additional details about the situation. "All of the confirmed cases are under the care of their physicians," she wrote. "We have been assured that they are either in process of completing the appropriate course of antibiotics or have already done so. Confirmed cases of pertussis have increased nationally over the past few years. Our district's identified cases are reflective of this national increase."

Prior to wide availability of pertussis vaccines in the 1940s, roughly 200 000 children were sickened with the disease each year, resulting in about 9000 fatalities, according to the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Now, the number of cases reported annually in the US ranges from 10 000 to 40 000. In 2017, for example, the CDC reported there were 18 975 cases and 13 fatalities in a nation of more than 330 million. A recent peak year for whooping cough was 2012 when there were 48 277 cases identified in the US -- the largest number since 1955 when there were 62 786.

"Since learning of each confirmed case, we have worked closely with the PA [Pennsylvania] Department of Health to ensure that all procedures and protocols related to pertussis are implemented," Palmer stated, adding that the district has stepped up its cleaning and is using a disinfectant known to be effective against the disease.

[Byline: Neil A Sheehan]

